In this and the next Ode, though Horace addresses Censorinus and Lollius, his words seem meant for Augustus. The Poet-Laureate hints pretty broadly to the Emperor that he is well aware of the value of the favour he is bestowing in writing this Book at his request. Censorinus was consul B.c. 8, and Vell. 2. 102 speaks of him as demerendis hominibus natum, ‘born to win men.⁹
